		<text>
		<body>
		<pb n="1"/>
		
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Charleston</placeName> <date>April 20/44</date></p>
			<p>Dear Friend</p>
		  <p rend="indent(2)">Aware of your anxi=<lb/>=ety &amp; deep interest you feel in our<lb/> cause &amp; the welfare &amp; continuation<lb/> of Judaism  I hasten to inform you<lb/> of the result of our law suit&#44; it<lb/> came on as <sic>apporated</sic> on <date>Monday</date><lb/> last &amp; continued before the court until<lb/> last night&#44; &amp; when I tell you that but<lb/> one witness was examined you cannot<lb/> but wonder how it should have so<lb/> occupied so much time&#44; especially<lb/> as the Judge ruled out the religious<lb/> questions&#44; but notwithstanding it was<lb/> incidentally introduced  by our counsel<lb/> the Examination of <persName>Mr. Valentine</persName> the<lb/> secretary occupied 2 days&#44; our consul<lb/> <persName>Mr. Memminger</persName> opened the case&#44; clearly<lb/> &amp; extensively did he go into the merits<lb/> not only in the law but in the changes<lb/> &amp; alterations of our sacred religion&#44; but after<lb/> a patent hearing the judge decided that<lb/> the religious charity or <sic>allecations</sic> could have<lb/> no bearing on the case that it was altogether<lb/> a matter of Law&#44; &amp; upon that only could the<lb/> case stand&#44; after the examination of <persName>Mr. V</persName></p>

		<pb n="2"/>
		
			<p><persName>Mr. Baily</persName> the opposite counsel declined<lb/> calling any counsel wherefore had<lb/> to abandon one of the charges of which<lb/> had been brought collusion &amp; fraud<lb/> by which means he secured the advantage<lb/> of the closing speech &#8211; It is the only<lb/> consolation [&#63;] our [&#63;]<lb/> left us to know that our <sic>counsellor</sic><lb/> <persName>Mr Memminger</persName> [&#63;] acquitted [&#63;]<lb/> with more than the [&#63;] with<lb/> which they have always been distinguished<lb/> The formers gentleman closing address<lb/> occupied 5 &#189; hours &#8211; The charge of the<lb/> [&#63;] was short but lucid &amp; his [&#63;]<lb/> &amp; conclusions were that the Board of trus<lb/>tees were not allowed &amp; could not<lb/> meet without the President &amp; that<lb/> no meeting could take place without<lb/> the consent of the President &#45;<lb/> Of course such a charge from the<lb/> [&#63;]&#44; if even the jury was any ways<lb/> favourably disposed toward us&#44; settled I<lb/> have no doubt in their minds any<lb/> doubt or feelings in their own <sic>judgement</sic><lb/> &amp; after [&#63;] our but a little time<lb/> brought in their verdict against us</p>
		  <p rend="indent(1)">My feelings as well as my friends are of<lb/> course [&#63;] and to say the least&#44; but<lb/> that is not the worst&#44; we all now at<lb/> sea again without a pilot&#44; nay without<lb/> a heaven to steer for&#44; we are in a<lb/> dreadful situation&#44; we know not what<lb/> is but to do. I truly regret that you</p>

		<pb n="3"/>
		
			<p>had not been allowed to have come<lb/> or your advice &amp; counsel at this<lb/> moment would have so beneficial<lb/> your consolation so healing to [&#63;]<lb/> wounded spirits&#44; nay to the preservation<lb/> of our future prosperity &#8211; Your administration [&#63;] have a great deal to answer for in<lb/> their indifference to their unfortunate Brethren<lb/> &amp; their sworn religion&#44; they have shown<lb/> thereby favourable to our opponents &amp; by<lb/> their refusal have encouraged them &amp; made<lb/> it apparent that your congregation were favourable<lb/> [&#63;] views &#8211; My feeling will not allow<lb/> me to carry this better to any extent I<lb/> therefore pray your continuance of health<lb/> &amp; life [&#63;] me to be your friend</p>
		  <p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Samuel Hart Sen.</persName></p>

			<p>Please send <persName>Mr. Rosenfeldt</persName> occident by mail</p>

			<p><persName>I.C. Levy</persName> &amp; <persName>Rev Dr Curtis</persName></p>
			<p>Discontinue</p>

			<p>I have had several [&#63;] of the Conciliator from <placeName>England</placeName>&#44; cost 8 shillings Sherl[&#63;] &amp; Lander [&#63;]<lb/> 42.67 I dont know your agent but if all the books<lb/> he sends you are in the same proportion. [&#63;] are dear enough &#8211;</p>

		<pb n="4"/>
		
			<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
		</body>
